Not only is this true, but &quot;putting a price on life&quot; is actually a serious issue that courts have to deal with.<br>
In cases of unnecessary loss of life (or permanent, crippling disability, such that it basically ends the victim's career), courts have repeatededly awarded sums to the defendent proportional to the income that they are expected to earn over the rest of their professional life.  (Note that this means that how much you receive depends heavily not only on how much you make, but how young you are -- how many &quot;good years&quot; you had left.)  The logic being roughly -- the family shouldn't have to be reduced to subsistence living just because some yahoo at the lawnmower factory didn't do the quality control tests right and now both of dad's arms are severed at the elbow.<br>
This leads to some nasty consequences.  Consider, for instance, the payout to families of Sept. 11 victims, whose inequitable distribution between the wealthy victims (bankers) and the poor victims (janitors) raised a few hackles.  In this case, the commission in charge of handing out the cash was in a tight spot: if they follow the precendent for payout proportional to salary, they look like the Avatar of Injustice.  On the other hand, if they paid significantly less to the wealthy families than they would normally get in a court settlement, the families will probably ignore the commision's offer and sue somebody else -- most likely the airlines -- directly, and stand to be awarded a lot more money (as well as the possibility of massive punitive damages) in an actual court.  So in some ways, the 9/11 payouts were designed to buy off the legal threats of the victims' families.<br>
Interesting reading on the subject is <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.newyorker.com/fact/content/?021125fa_fact">a profile of Kenneth Feinberg</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->, who oversees the 9/11 Victim's Compensation Fund, that the New Yorker ran last November.<br>
So as for being unable to put a price on life: that's not true.  We can, and we do -- it just may not be the right one. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub27.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nandarie>Nandarie</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style='color:orange;'>Tavern Resident</span></span><br>  Posts: 2802<br> <font color=#6FB8DD>(3/17/03 10:46 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/fthesaryrntavernthefurnace.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3168.topic&index=56>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www.mwscomp.com/movies/grail/jpgs/timencha.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: A * B = C</span><hr size=1> good post <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=205399">My Gear Sucks less now!</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i></i></td></tr></table><br><font color=#6FB8DD>- </font><a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern>The Saryrn Tavern</a><font color=#6FB8DD> - </font><a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/fthesaryrntavernthefurnace>The Blast Furnace</a><font color=#6FB8DD> - </font><br><br><br><br>Powered By <a href=http://www.ezboard.com/>ezboard®</a> Ver. 7.246g<br>Copyright ©1999-2003 ezboard, Inc.</center></body></html>  

